# PRACTICE: Links

Links are a key part of a Website.

Here's a link to my website:

```html
<a href="https://flaviocopes.com">flaviocopes.com</a>
```

Links can be relative to the site, by omitting the domain:

```html
<a href="/blog">blog</a>
```

Try this example:

```html
<html>
  <body>
    <h2>Links</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <a href="<https://flaviocopes.com>">flaviocopes.com</a>
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/blog">blog</a>
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="mailto:flavio@flaviocopes.com">email flavio</a>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </body>
</html>
```

![Screen Shot 2020-04-14 at 17.36.09.png](PRACTICE%20Links%201902767ad7e381ee9174c2260377c933/Screen_Shot_2020-04-14_at_17.36.09.png)

Links can also point to resources on the same page, using the `#` symbol:

```html
<a href="#first-chapter">First chapter</a>
```

In this case, an anchor element without `href` attribute must be present:

```html
<a id="first-chapter"></a>
```

Once you click the `a` with the `href` attribute, the browser will then move to the `a` element with the `id` attribute it points to.

